## Lessons Learned

Completing this homelab reinforced how different working with real hardware is compared to simulations like Packet Tracer. Physical layer issues such as cabling problems and interface negotiation behavior introduced challenges that are difficult to replicate in virtual environments. This experience taught me the importance of slowing down and verifying configurations with `show` commands after each step rather than assuming the network will behave as expected. I also found that documenting mistakes was extremely valuable, since many of the most meaningful lessons came from troubleshooting errors rather than from the configurations that worked immediately.

Throughout the process I became much more comfortable using the `no` command to correct misconfigurations and rebuild parts of the configuration when necessary. The lab also reinforced how small mistakes—such as an incorrect OSPF wildcard mask or a VLAN assignment error—can prevent critical network functions from working. Working through these issues gave me a better appreciation for how complex traditional network management can become, and it made me realize how difficult it would be to manage very large networks purely through manual configuration.

After completing this project, I also developed a stronger appreciation for why software-defined networking (SDN) and centralized automation tools are so valuable in modern infrastructure. When managing networks through traditional CLI configurations, it becomes easy to introduce configuration drift or small mistakes that can impact connectivity. This lab helped me better understand the operational challenges network engineers face and why automation, abstraction, and centralized management are increasingly important for managing large-scale environments.
